{"key":"post-19740672","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>19740672</id>\n<content>The only reason you had a higher contamination rate is because of using fresh coffee grinds in a bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; Once you get it damp, the coffee 'brews' and spits too much liquid coffee into your bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; Always use spent coffee grinds as a bulk substrate ingredient and save the fresh coffee for grains.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To the OP, I use coffee grinds every day, but after brewing, they get mixed into the rest of the substrate and pasteurized or sterilized together.&amp;nbsp; Do the same thing after thawing out frozen ones.&amp;nbsp; Since coffee grinds are too nutritious as a substrate by themselves, you're always going to be mixing them with something else so pasteurize it all together.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>19740679</next>\n<prev>19740665</prev>\n<first>19740301</first>\n<last>19741022</last>\n<when>1395685279</when>\n<utime>03/24/14 09:21 PM</utime>\n</post>"}